      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Obviously I=E2=80=99ll miss this but at least it is going to go  exactly as=
 long as possible:

Elon Musk yesterday pledged to close the acquisition of Twitter Inc. by Fri=
day in a video conference call with bankers helping fund the deal, accordin=
g to people with knowledge of the matter, Bloomberg News reports.
The banks, which are providing $13 billion of debt financing, have finished=
 putting together the final credit agreement and are in the process of sign=
ing the documentation, one of the last steps before actually sending the ca=
sh to Musk, said the people.
The Wall Street lenders, led by Morgan Stanley, had already been preparing =
in recent weeks to fund the debt, Bloomberg previously reported. But nothin=
g is ever certain with Musk, the mercurial billionaire who only weeks ago w=
as seeking to back out of the deal. These latest developments suggest he is=
 in the final stages of closing the transaction by a court-issued Oct. 28 d=
eadline.
The banks are expected to receive one of the last formalities -- a borrowin=
g notice -- on Tuesday, and the cash is expected to be held in escrow on Th=
ursday, the people said.

Is this deal going to close on Thursday? Oh no, no no no. He=E2=80=99s got =
until 5 p.m. on Friday. A plausible time to close would be 4:45 on Friday, =
possibly 4:20. Really 5:30 is not entirely off the table; if they are all d=
oing good amicable closing stuff at 4:59 Twitter is not going to go running=
 to the judge to complain about it being a few minutes late.
  [1]
=C2=A0Why close on Thursday and take all the suspense out of it?=C2=A0
Though, really, the suspense is pretty much out of it. The key sentence her=
e is not =E2=80=9CElon Musk yesterday pledged to close the acquisition of T=
witter Inc. by Friday=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9CThe banks =E2=80=A6 are =
in the process of signing the documentation.=E2=80=9D The=C2=A0main=C2=A0 s=
ource of suspense, since Musk said he planned to close, is whether his bank=
s would fund their $13 billion commitments.
  [2]
=C2=A0I figured they would, but people had doubts, and Musk=E2=80=99s lawye=
rs were a little bit coy about it. Could the banks have said something like=
 =E2=80=9Cthe deal has been terminated=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthere was a mat=
erial adverse effect=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwait Twitter has bots=E2=80=9D an=
d refused to fund? I mean, no, not really, but if they=C2=A0were=C2=A0going=
 to do that it would have been before drafting and signing the credit agree=
ments. The banks are in now.
Also:
On the call, Musk also promised to help the banks market the debt to money =
managers after the deal closes, the people said.
I am very much looking forward to reading those marketing documents. =E2=80=
=9CSure Twitter was=C2=A0a huge fraud, but now it=E2=80=99s great, so give =
me my money.=E2=80=9D
Still, there=E2=80=99s some ancillary suspense, like who else=C2=A0will kic=
k in some money to pay part of Musk=E2=80=99s equity check. Here=E2=80=99s =
  one guy who=E2=80=99s a maybe:

Binance Holdings Ltd.=E2=80=99s chief executive officer said he thinks he w=
ill stick with Elon Musk=E2=80=99s proposed $44 billion buyout of Twitter I=
nc. amid potential concerns from Washington about foreign investors backing=
 the bid. =C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI think so,=E2=80=9D Changpeng Zhao said when asked if he will sta=
nd by his financial commitment to Musk. Zhao spoke in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,=
 where he was attending the kingdom=E2=80=99s Future Investment Initiative =
conference on Tuesday.

And here=E2=80=99s a yes:

Roelof Botha, the head of Sequoia Capital, said he thinks there are large i=
mprovements to be made for Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s current business and that=
 Elon Musk=E2=80=99s takeover bid for the social-media company will be a su=
ccess.
Mr. Botha, speaking at The Wall Street Journal=E2=80=99s Tech Live conferen=
ce, said he thought Twitter could find better ways to make money beyond adv=
ertising and improve its product. Sequoia has committed $800 million for th=
e deal. The funding is set to come from Sequoia=E2=80=99s main venture fund=
s, its wealth management business called Heritage, and its crossover fund S=
equoia Capital Global Equities. ...
=E2=80=9CElon has succeeded in many different industries,=E2=80=9D Mr. Both=
a said. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s an incredible first-principles thinker.=E2=80=
=9D
Mr. Botha said Sequoia ran financial models and spoke to current and former=
 employees when examining the potential of the Twitter deal. He said he had=
 spoken to Mr. Musk about potential changes to the Twitter business, includ=
ing around payments integration, and believed that Mr. Musk could address i=
ssues around account verification, such as abuse and spam, and introduce ne=
w monetization strategies such as using subscriptions.
The approach of some investors in evaluating the deal has drawn significant=
 attention.=C2=A0Marc Andreessen, the co-founder of venture firm Andreessen=
 Horowitz, wrote to Mr. Musk in April that he was willing to commit $250 mi=
llion for the Twitter deal, with =E2=80=9Cno additional work required,=E2=
=80=9D according to documents made public in the recent Twitter-Musk lawsui=
t. Andreessen agreed to ultimately invest $400 million.

This is the difference between investing your own money and investing as a =
fiduciary for your fund=E2=80=99s limited partners. Elon Musk, when he anno=
unced his plans to buy Twitter, said things like =E2=80=9Cthis is not a way=
 to sort of make money=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cyou don=E2=80=99t care about t=
he economics at all=E2=80=9D; more recently  he said that he is =E2=80=9Cob=
viously overpaying.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s fine! He=E2=80=99s rich, he=E2=
=80=99s using his own money, and if he wants to overpay for Twitter because=
 he enjoys tweeting or thinks it=E2=80=99s good for free speech or whatever=
, that=E2=80=99s his business.
But Roelof Botha can=E2=80=99t go to his LPs and say =E2=80=9Coh we=E2=80=
=99re not in this deal to make money, we don=E2=80=99t care about the econo=
mics at all.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s their money! He has to say things like =
=E2=80=9Cwe ran financial models.=E2=80=9D Did they? Sure, probably. I have=
 previously defended Musk=E2=80=99s co-investors=E2=80=99 somewhat lackadai=
sical approach to due diligence on this deal.  I wrote:
