The way it works if you=E2=80=99re Mark Zuckerberg is that you have a busin=
ess, and it makes about $30 billion a year in profit, but that $30 billion =
is not direct deposited into your bank account. For one thing, the money go=
es back into the business, to pay for  legs or whatever. For another thing,=
 you =E2=80=9Chave=E2=80=9D the business in a loose sense, but you are not =
the sole proprietor of the business; for various reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0to =
attract employees and pay for acquisitions and raise money =E2=80=94 you ha=
ve given a lot of shares in the business to other people, and you only actu=
ally own  about 13% of it. So in some rough sense your share of the annual =
profits from the business is about $4 billion a year, but again you don=E2=
=80=99t get that in cash. The business does not pay any dividends to shareh=
olders, and your annual salary is $1, so there is no real cash involved. Ho=
w rich are you?
The answer is =E2=80=9Cextremely rich,=E2=80=9D though we can give a better=
 answer;=C2=A0the Bloomberg Billionaires Index lists Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s w=
ealth as $51.6 billion.=C2=A0We can do this because your business, Meta Pla=
tforms Inc., is a=C2=A0company, and there are ways to calculate the value o=
f a company. Simplistically, a big stable company like Meta is worth some m=
ultiple of its annual profits; let=E2=80=99s say a reasonable multiple woul=
d be about 12. Your $30-billion-a-year business is worth about $360 billion=
 or so, you own 13% of it, so you =E2=80=9Chave=E2=80=9D about $48=C2=A0bil=
lion.
  [3]
=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not $48 billion of cash, though; it=E2=80=99s a 13% cl=
aim on a stream of $30 billion of annual profits that are reinvested into a=
 business, and finance says that that claim is worth $48 billion.
Also of course Meta is a=C2=A0public=C2=A0company, so that number is=C2=A0n=
ot just my estimate of what that stream of profits is worth; that number is=
 what the market says it=E2=80=99s worth, and what, roughly speaking, you c=
ould actually sell it for today. If you went and sold your entire stake in =
Meta today you probably wouldn=E2=80=99t get $48 billion for it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the price would probably go down =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you went and s=
old 0.1% of your stake today you=E2=80=99d probably get right around $48 mi=
llion for it. So it is not particularly misleading to say that you have $48=
 billion, even though you don=E2=80=99t actually have $48 billion. You don=
=E2=80=99t have $48 billion in cash, but it=E2=80=99s almost true that you=
=C2=A0have $48 billion in spending power.
And then you add a few billion dollars of miscellaneous cash and assets, th=
e sort of wealth that=C2=A0you accumulate over the years if you own a $48 b=
illion stake in a business, and you get $51.6 billion. Virtually all of you=
r=C2=A0wealth is the Meta stake, though not quite all of it.
The way it works if you=E2=80=99re me is that I=C2=A0come into work, and I =
write a newsletter, and I get $X per year in salary for it, and that $X per=
 year is in fact direct deposited into my bank account, after deducting tax=
es and stuff. And then I spend most of it, and at the end of the year my ba=
nk account has grown by $Y (Y < X). And over the years my bank account grow=
s by, you know, $Y1, $Y2, $Y3, etc., a different=C2=A0$Y each year. How ric=
h am I? Well, simplistically, my wealth is $Y1 + $Y2 + =E2=80=A6=C2=A0+ $Yn=
, one $Y for each year that I have worked. My wealth is the sum of my past =
earnings, minus my past expenses.
These are very different calculations. Virtually all of Zuckerberg=E2=80=99=
s wealth comes from=C2=A0the future earnings of his business: Meta is worth=
 12 times its annual profit=C2=A0because the market expects it to continue =
to make (and grow) that sort of annual profit for many years,
  [4]
=C2=A0and is willing to pay for those future earnings today. All of my=C2=
=A0wealth comes from my past earnings. I mean, in some important theoretica=
l economic sense my worth comes from my future earnings, but not in the col=
loquial sense where, like, an online net worth calculator asks me for my sa=
lary and then multiplies it by 12.=C2=A0My=C2=A0net worth is roughly my ban=
k account; Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s is his share of future earnings.
Some people=E2=80=99s net worth comes from their past earnings, and some pe=
ople=E2=80=99s net worth comes from their future earnings. The difference i=
s not entirely quantitative =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s about capital=C2=A0=
ownership and corporate structure and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is par=
tly quantitative. As a rough rule of thumb, if you make $100,000 per year, =
you are probably not a millionaire, unless you also happen to have $1 milli=
on in the bank. If you make $100 million per year, you are probably a billi=
onaire, even if you don=E2=80=99t have $1 billion in the bank.=C2=A0
There comes a point in the life of an enormous celebrity where you switch=
=C2=A0over between these calculation methods. You record an album, you get =
paid a million dollars for it, you say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m a millionaire.=
=E2=80=9D You do a collaboration with a clothing line, they pay you $10 mil=
lion for it, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Csweet now I have $10 million.=E2=
=80=9D You sign a contract with a sneaker company to pay you $100 million a=
 year, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Csweet $100 million,=E2=80=9D and   Forb=
es shows up and says =E2=80=9Cnope, wrong, now you=E2=80=99re a billionaire=
.=E2=80=9D That $100 million got deposited in your bank account, but now yo=
u are a=C2=A0business,
  [5]
=C2=A0and so you=E2=80=99re valued at 12 times earnings or whatever. That c=
ontract makes you worth $1.2 billion. Congratulations!
Also though if that contract gets=C2=A0canceled, the number in your bank ac=
count does not go down, yet you lose a billion dollars.
Ye, the artist formerly known as Kanye West, has made a lot of money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0hundreds of millions of dollars =E2=80=94=C2=A0in his career in mu=
sic and fashion, but he also stood to make a lot of=C2=A0future=C2=A0money =
in that business, so by   the rules of   this game he was=C2=A0a billionair=
e. And then he got really into anti-Semitism, which zeroed a lot of those f=
uture earnings, which made him   not a billionaire anymore:

For years, it was an open question just how much Ye, the mercurial rapper f=
ormerly known as Kanye West, might be worth. He said he was a billionaire m=
ultiple times over thanks to a handful of lucrative corporate deals, most n=
otably his Yeezy brand with Adidas AG.
It was hardly a stretch: The Yeezy business alone earned more than $500 mil=
lion in total royalty payments and marketing fees over the first four full =
years of the Adidas deal through 2020, according to a document prepared by =
UBS Group AG. He had partnerships with Gap Inc. and Kering SA=E2=80=99s Bal=
enciaga fashion label, while an unaudited balance sheet of his finances rev=
iewed by Bloomberg in 2021 showed that he had $122 million in cash and stoc=
k.=C2=A0
The one big risk to any net-worth estimate =E2=80=94 which is now playing o=
ut in real-time =E2=80=94 was that he would self-destruct.=C2=A0
Adidas said on Tuesday it would halt all payments to Ye and stop the Yeezy =
business immediately after a wave of offensive behavior, including antisemi=
