      Distressed debt
   =20
 =20

I have in the past  described the fundamental theory of modern distressed d=
ebt investing:
=09A company borrows $1 billion, in a syndicated loan or a bond issue, from=
 a bunch of different investors.=09As is customary, the loan agreement or b=
ond indenture says =E2=80=9Cthis agreement may be amended by a majority of =
the investors.=E2=80=9D=09Time passes and the company runs into some troubl=
e.=09The company goes out to 51% of the investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0holders of=
 $510 million of the bond or loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0and says: =E2=80=9CPsst. W=
e will pay you back 110=C2=A0cents on the dollar =E2=80=94=C2=A0$561 millio=
n total =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you agree to let us stiff the other guys.=E2=80=
=9D=09So the 51% holders vote to amend the agreement to say =E2=80=9Cthese =
holders will get 110 cents on the dollar, and the other holders will get ze=
ro.=E2=80=9D=09The other 49% are really mad=C2=A0and surprised.=09The amend=
ment works, 51% of the holders make a nice profit, 49% of the holders lose =
all their money, and the company pockets the extra $439 million.

Every time I write about this, I have to stress that this theory is not rea=
lly=C2=A0true. You can=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0do=C2=A0that. The way it works=
 is that the debt agreements do=C2=A0generally let holders of the majority =
(or sometimes some supermajority) of the debt vote to amend the terms, but =
not all=C2=A0of the terms. Some terms can=E2=80=99t be amended by a vote; e=
very holder has to agree to have those terms changed for their debt. Paymen=
t of principal is definitely always in that latter, inviolable category; ho=
lders of 51% of the debt can=E2=80=99t vote to stiff the other 49%.
The game is to get=C2=A0close=C2=A0to that, by amending a thing that=C2=A0c=
an=C2=A0be amended. Popular approaches generally involve collateral: You ha=
ve some debt that is secured by some assets, and 51% of the debt votes to r=
emove that security (or allow more senior debt, etc.) and give it to some o=
ther debt (that they hold). The 51% end up with debt that is good and secur=
ed by good assets; the 49% end up with debt that is bad and secured by tumb=
leweeds. This is good for the 51% and bad for the 49% and good in a sense f=
or the company (which gets some extra money or extended repayment terms fro=
m the 51%), but the debt of the 49% is still outstanding and it still needs=
 to be paid. If =E2=80=94=C2=A0as happens pretty often in these situations =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the company ends up going=C2=A0bankrupt=C2=A0then sure, yes,=
 the 49% get less, perhaps nothing. But if =E2=80=94=C2=A0as is also pretty=
 common =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company is trying to=C2=A0avoid=C2=A0bankruptcy,=
 it has to keep paying the 49%, and there=E2=80=99s some chance that the co=
mpany will succeed and it will all work out fine for the 49%.
Here=E2=80=99s a new one to me (from LevFin Insights via  Sujeet Indap):
Diebold Nixdorf, in announcing a multi-faceted liability management exercis=
e that includes an equity component for bondholders to address near-term ma=
turities and raise $400 million, got creative in addressing potential holdo=
uts for its 2024 notes. The ATM maker is seeking consents from those partic=
ipating in the deal to =E2=80=9Cextend the grace period under the 2024 Seni=
or Notes Indenture applicable with respect to defaults in payment of intere=
st=C2=A0to run until the maturity date of the 2024 Senior Notes,=E2=80=9D a=
ccording to its 8-K filing.
Here is  the 8-K. If you agree to the exchange, you get=C2=A0some new longe=
r-dated notes with second-lien security, along with some warrants on the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s stock. If you don=E2=80=99t agree to the exchange, the peop=
le who=C2=A0do=C2=A0agree vote to make it so that the company doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to pay you interest until 2024. You can=E2=80=99t have a majority=
 of the note holders vote to say =E2=80=9Cthe company doesn=E2=80=99t have =
to pay interest to the minority,=E2=80=9D but you can =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguab=
ly =E2=80=94=C2=A0have a majority vote to change the technical provisions g=
overning default to say =E2=80=9Cif the company doesn=E2=80=99t pay interes=
t, you can=E2=80=99t do anything about it=C2=A0until 2024.=E2=80=9D (I am n=
ot sure this is right =E2=80=94 the indenture (section 9.02) says that hold=
ers of a majority of the 2024 notes can amend the notes with a limited list=
 of things that=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0be amended; some of those things in=
clude amendments to =E2=80=9Creduce the stated rate of interest or extend t=
he stated time for payment of interest on any Note=E2=80=9D or to =E2=80=9C=
waive a Default or Event of Default in the payment of principal of, premium=
, if any, or interest on the Notes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I guess you =
can try.) It is not perfect, but it does get a bit closer to the ideal of =
=E2=80=9Ca majority of the bondholders vote to=C2=A0zero=C2=A0the minority.=
=E2=80=9D
Though it=E2=80=99s not that bad. There are two ways to approach these tran=
sactions. One really is that you get 51% of the bondholders to vote to stif=
f the other 49%: There is limited money to go around, and if you=C2=A0take=
=C2=A0money from the 49% that gives you some money to pay to the 51% (for t=
heir vote) and some money to give to the company (to spend on staying afloa=
t). In that sort of transaction, you=C2=A0want=C2=A0a thin majority; you wa=
nt to stiff 49% of the bondholders because that leaves more money for every=
one else.
The other is that you go out to=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the bondholders and ask th=
em to vote for an extension, restructuring, etc., and you say =E2=80=9Cby t=
he way, if we get a majority to approve this extension, we will also stiff =
the minority.=E2=80=9D You pressure bondholders into approving the deal, bu=
t if they approve the deal they get what everyone else gets. That is what i=
s happening here. The goal is to get everyone to agree to the deal, not to =
get a small majority and stop paying the rest.

