<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way it works if you=E2=80=99re Mark Zucker=
berg is that you have a business, and it makes about $30 billion a year in =
profit, but that $30 billion is not direct deposited into your bank account=
. For one thing, the money goes back into the business, to pay for <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29501026.287508/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9tYXJrLXp1Y2tlcmJlcmctbWV0YXZlcnNlLWxlZ3Mt=
bW90aW9uLWNhcHR1cmUtYW5pbWF0aW9uLTIwMjItMTA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB277064=
77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> legs</a> or whatever. For another thing, you =E2=80=9Chave=E2=
=80=9D the business in a loose sense, but you are not the sole proprietor o=
f the business; for various reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0to attract employees and=
 pay for acquisitions and raise money =E2=80=94 you have given a lot of sha=
res in the business to other people, and you only actually own <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29501026.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMjY4MDEvMDAwMTMyNjgwMTIyMDAwMDQzL=
21ldGEyMDIyZGVmaW5pdGl2ZXByb3h5c3RhLmh0bSNpMDQ2OTMzZWY3YzI2NDc3ZTljOGExMDhk=
OTM3ZTI5NGRfNDA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6f07bb7d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> about 13% of it=
</a>. So in some rough sense your share of the annual profits from the busi=
ness is about $4 billion a year, but again you don=E2=80=99t get that in ca=
sh. The business does not pay any dividends to shareholders, and your annua=
l salary is $1, so there is no real cash involved. How rich are you?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The answer is =E2=80=9Cextremely rich,=E2=80=
=9D though we can give a better answer;=C2=A0the Bloomberg Billionaires Ind=
ex lists Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s wealth as $51.6 billion.=C2=A0We can do this =
because your business, Meta Platforms Inc., is a=C2=A0<em>company</em>, and=
 there are ways to calculate the value of a company. Simplistically, a big =
stable company like Meta is worth some multiple of its annual profits; let=
=E2=80=99s say a reasonable multiple would be about 12. Your $30-billion-a-=
year business is worth about $360 billion or so, you own 13% of it, so you =
=E2=80=9Chave=E2=80=9D about $48=C2=A0billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not $48 billion of cash, though; it=E2=80=99s a 13=
% claim on a stream of $30 billion of annual profits that are reinvested in=
to a business, and finance says that that claim is worth $48 billion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also of course Meta is a=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0=
</em>company, so that number is=C2=A0not just my estimate of what that stre=
am of profits is worth; that number is what the market says it=E2=80=99s wo=
rth, and what, roughly speaking, you could actually sell it for today. If y=
ou went and sold your entire stake in Meta today you probably wouldn=E2=80=
=99t get $48 billion for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0the price would probably go down=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you went and sold 0.1% of your stake today you=E2=80=
=99d probably get right around $48 million for it. So it is not particularl=
y misleading to say that you have $48 billion, even though you don=E2=80=99=
t actually have $48 billion. You don=E2=80=99t have $48 billion in cash, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s almost true that you=C2=A0have $48 billion in spending power=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then you add a few billion dollars of misc=
ellaneous cash and assets, the sort of wealth that=C2=A0you accumulate over=
 the years if you own a $48 billion stake in a business, and you get $51.6 =
billion. Virtually all of your=C2=A0wealth is the Meta stake, though not qu=
ite all of it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way it works if you=E2=80=99re me is that =
I=C2=A0come into work, and I write a newsletter, and I get $X per year in s=
alary for it, and that $X per year is in fact direct deposited into my bank=
 account, after deducting taxes and stuff. And then I spend most of it, and=
 at the end of the year my bank account has grown by $Y (Y &lt; X). And ove=
r the years my bank account grows by, you know, $Y1, $Y2, $Y3, etc., a diff=
erent=C2=A0$Y each year. How rich am I? Well, simplistically, my wealth is =
$Y1 + $Y2 + =E2=80=A6=C2=A0+ $Yn, one $Y for each year that I have worked. =
My wealth is the sum of my past earnings, minus my past expenses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are very different calculations. Virtual=
ly all of Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s wealth comes from=C2=A0<em>the future earnin=
gs of his business: </em>Meta is worth 12 times its annual profit=C2=A0beca=
use the market expects it to continue to make (and grow) that sort of annua=
l profit for many years,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and is willing to pay for those future earnings today. All of <em=
>my=C2=A0</em>wealth comes from my past earnings. I mean, in some important=
 theoretical economic sense my worth comes from my future earnings, but not=
 in the colloquial sense where, like, an online net worth calculator asks m=
e for my salary and then multiplies it by 12.=C2=A0<em>My=C2=A0</em>net wor=
th is roughly my bank account; Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s is his share of future =
earnings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some people=E2=80=99s net worth comes from the=
ir past earnings, and some people=E2=80=99s net worth comes from their futu=
re earnings. The difference is not entirely quantitative =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=
=E2=80=99s about capital=C2=A0ownership and corporate structure and so fort=
h =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is partly quantitative. As a rough rule of thumb, i=
f you make $100,000 per year, you are probably not a millionaire, unless yo=
u also happen to have $1 million in the bank. If you make $100 million per =
year, you are probably a billionaire, even if you don=E2=80=99t have $1 bil=
lion in the bank.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There comes a point in the life of an enormous=
 celebrity where you switch=C2=A0over between these calculation methods. Yo=
u record an album, you get paid a million dollars for it, you say =E2=80=9C=
I=E2=80=99m a millionaire.=E2=80=9D You do a collaboration with a clothing =
line, they pay you $10 million for it, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Csweet n=
ow I have $10 million.=E2=80=9D You sign a contract with a sneaker company =
to pay you $100 million a year, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Csweet $100 mil=
lion,=E2=80=9D and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/29501026.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
