<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Distressed debt</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have in the past <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29501026.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDcvZGlzdHJlc3NlZC1kZWJ0LWRlYWwtbWFr=
ZXMtcGVvcGxlLW1hZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWl=
sJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbm=
V5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4508ed1b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> described</a> the fun=
damental theory of modern distressed debt investing:</p>
<blockquote><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; marg=
in: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company borrows $1 bill=
ion, in a syndicated loan or a bond issue, from a bunch of different invest=
ors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">As is customary, the loan agr=
eement or bond indenture says =E2=80=9Cthis agreement may be amended by a m=
ajority of the investors.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Time passes and the company runs into some trouble.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The company goes out to 51% of the investors =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0holders of $510 million of the bond or loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0and says: =
=E2=80=9CPsst. We will pay you back 110=C2=A0cents on the dollar =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0$561 million total =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you agree to let us stiff the ot=
her guys.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the 51% hold=
ers vote to amend the agreement to say =E2=80=9Cthese holders will get 110 =
cents on the dollar, and the other holders will get zero.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The other 49% are really mad=C2=A0and surp=
rised.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The amendment works, 51% of=
 the holders make a nice profit, 49% of the holders lose all their money, a=
nd the company pockets the extra $439 million.</li>
</ol></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every time I write about this, I have to stres=
s that this theory is not really=C2=A0<em>true</em>. You can=E2=80=99t real=
ly=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>that. The way it works is that the debt agreements=
 <em>do=C2=A0</em>generally let holders of the majority (or sometimes some =
supermajority) of the debt vote to amend the terms, but not <em>all=C2=A0</=
em>of the terms. Some terms can=E2=80=99t be amended by a vote; every holde=
r has to agree to have those terms changed for their debt. Payment of princ=
ipal is definitely always in that latter, inviolable category; holders of 5=
1% of the debt can=E2=80=99t vote to stiff the other 49%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The game is to get=C2=A0<em>close=C2=A0</em>to=
 that, by amending a thing that=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>be amended. Popular =
approaches generally involve collateral: You have some debt that is secured=
 by some assets, and 51% of the debt votes to remove that security (or allo=
w more senior debt, etc.) and give it to some other debt (that they hold). =
The 51% end up with debt that is good and secured by good assets; the 49% e=
nd up with debt that is bad and secured by tumbleweeds. This is good for th=
e 51% and bad for the 49% and good in a sense for the company (which gets s=
ome extra money or extended repayment terms from the 51%), but the debt of =
the 49% is still outstanding and it still needs to be paid. If =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0as happens pretty often in these situations =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company e=
nds up going=C2=A0<em>bankrupt=C2=A0</em>then sure, yes, the 49% get less, =
perhaps nothing. But if =E2=80=94=C2=A0as is also pretty common =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the company is trying to=C2=A0<em>avoid=C2=A0</em>bankruptcy, it has =
to keep paying the 49%, and there=E2=80=99s some chance that the company wi=
ll succeed and it will all work out fine for the 49%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a new one to me (from LevFin In=
sights via <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2950102=
6.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9zaW5kYXAvc3RhdHVzLzE1ODM3ODgyOTk2MTI1OD=
U5ODQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c21e183" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Sujeet Indap</a>):</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Diebold Nixdorf, in announcing a m=
ulti-faceted liability management exercise that includes an equity componen=
t for bondholders to address near-term maturities and raise $400 million, g=
ot creative in addressing potential holdouts for its 2024 notes. The ATM ma=
ker is seeking consents from those participating in the deal to =E2=80=9Cex=
tend the grace period under the 2024 Senior Notes Indenture applicable with=
 respect to defaults in payment of interest=C2=A0to run until the maturity =
date of the 2024 Senior Notes,=E2=80=9D according to its 8-K filing.</p></b=
lockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29501026.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0Fy=
Y2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMjg4MjMvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjY1NjkxL2Q0MDY3NjJkOGsuaHR=
t/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB702bdca2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the 8-K</a>. If you agree to =
the exchange, you get=C2=A0some new longer-dated notes with second-lien sec=
urity, along with some warrants on the company=E2=80=99s stock. If you don=
=E2=80=99t agree to the exchange, the people who=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>agre=
e vote to make it so that the company doesn=E2=80=99t have to pay you inter=
est until 2024. You can=E2=80=99t have a majority of the note holders vote =
to say =E2=80=9Cthe company doesn=E2=80=99t have to pay interest to the min=
ority,=E2=80=9D but you can =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguably =E2=80=94=C2=A0have a m=
ajority vote to change the technical provisions governing default to say =
=E2=80=9Cif the company doesn=E2=80=99t pay interest, you can=E2=80=99t do =
anything about it=C2=A0until 2024.=E2=80=9D (I am not sure this is right =
=E2=80=94 the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2950=
1026.287508/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzI4ODIzLzA=
wMDExOTMxMjUxNjU0NjU3Mi9kMTgwODE1ZGV4NDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea9b=
05f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">indenture</a> (section 9.02) says that holders of a majority =
of the 2024 notes can amend the notes with a limited list of things that=C2=
=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>be amended; some of those things include ame=
ndments to =E2=80=9Creduce the stated rate of interest or extend the stated=
 time for payment of interest on any Note=E2=80=9D or to =E2=80=9Cwaive a D=
efault or Event of Default in the payment of principal of, premium, if any,=
 or interest on the Notes=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I guess you can try.)=
 It is not perfect, but it does get a bit closer to the ideal of =E2=80=9Ca=
 majority of the bondholders vote to=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=A0</em>the minority.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though it=E2=80=99s not that bad. There are tw=
o ways to approach these transactions. One really is that you get 51% of th=
e bondholders to vote to stiff the other 49%: There is limited money to go =
around, and if you=C2=A0<em>take=C2=A0</em>money from the 49% that gives yo=
u some money to pay to the 51% (for their vote) and some money to give to t=
he company (to spend on staying afloat). In that sort of transaction, you=
=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>a thin majority; you want to stiff 49% of the bond=
holders because that leaves more money for everyone else.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that you go out to=C2=A0<em>all=
=C2=A0</em>of the bondholders and ask them to vote for an extension, restru=
cturing, etc., and you say =E2=80=9Cby the way, if we get a majority to app=
rove this extension, we will also stiff the minority.=E2=80=9D You pressure=
 bondholders into approving the deal, but if they approve the deal they get=
 what everyone else gets. That is what is happening here. The <em>goal</em>=
 is to get everyone to agree to the deal, not to get a small majority and s=
top paying the rest.</p>
