<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively the price of a diamond has three c=
omponents:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Broad diamond prices, driven by thing=
s like macroeconomic conditions, industrial uses for diamonds, successful b=
randing of diamonds as necessary for marriages, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The specific characteristics (size, clarity, cut, etc.) =
of the particular diamond.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Probabl=
y a retail markup.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a quantitative hedge fund manager y=
ou might think something like =E2=80=9Csure, this looks like a familiar pro=
blem, I will get a time series of diamond prices and come up with a pricing=
 algorithm. A two-carat VVS1 diamond is historically worth about X times as=
 much as a one-carat SI1 diamond, for instance, and with enough data points=
 I can extract the components of diamond price.=E2=80=9D And then you can h=
ave a diamond index that tracks Component 1 =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe pri=
ce of diamonds,=E2=80=9D generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also some sort of cal=
culator that can price any individual diamond based on the index. (A two-ca=
rat VVS1 diamond is worth Y% of the index price, etc.) And then you can tur=
n diamonds into a financial commodity and trade derivatives on them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess it=E2=80=99s hard though. Here is a fu=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29501026.287508/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9kaWFtb25kLXRyYWRpbmctZmlybS1jcmFmdHM=
tZ2Vtc3RvbmVzLWludG8tYS1jb21tb2RpdHktMTE2NjY3MDI5MjM_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eW=
Fob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93c48ec8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal sto=
ry</a> about=C2=A0=E2=80=9CCormac Kinney, founder and chief executive of Di=
amond Standard, which has been buying about 10,000 diamonds a week and sell=
ing plastic-encased, equally valued clusters to investors,=E2=80=9D and who=
 now plans to launch an exchange-traded fund:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Kinney, a computer scientist, believes he =
has cracked the code to commoditizing diamonds. He has run a quantitative h=
edge fund and created and sold trading programs and other software, includi=
ng to News Corp, which owns The Wall Street Journal. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI put together a huge spreadsheet of =
different diamonds and analyzed how their price changed based on carat, the=
 color, clarity,=E2=80=9D Mr. Kinney said. =E2=80=9CIt was basically to exp=
lore, what are the trade-offs that you have with a diamond? What makes the =
price go up or down?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Kinney decided that the way to commoditize=
 diamonds was to group them in equally valued clusters. To do that, he woul=
d need to create a type of yield curve that organized values by thousands o=
f combinations of characteristics, so that diamonds could be organized in e=
qual bunches.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The values were constantly changing. The data =
set could never be completed. He decided he couldn=E2=80=99t write an algor=
ithm to produce the curve. Diamond Standard would discover prices instead b=
y buying thousands of diamonds.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I particularly enjoyed this consultant saying =
you=E2=80=99ll probably want to throw some machine learning at it:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Diamonds are also idiosyncratic, with thousand=
s of combinations of color, clarity, carat and cut, and usually valued by s=
ubjective appraisal. You can cut a gold bar in two and the halves will equa=
l the whole, but two half-carat diamonds don=E2=80=99t add up to a 1-carat =
stone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fungibility, more than opaque pricing or illiq=
uidity, is the biggest hurdle for investment diamonds, said Olya Linde, a Z=
urich-based partner at consulting firm Bain &amp; Co., who specializes in e=
nergy and natural resources.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf anyone solves that, that=E2=80=99s=
 the first big step toward unlocking the investment demand,=E2=80=9D she sa=
id. =E2=80=9CThis is where the real technology, artificial intelligence and=
 machine learning, probably can come in.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the other real technology is=C2=A0<e=
m>financial=C2=A0</em>technology. You sell your Aggregated Diamond Clusters=
 to get a price for diamonds, then you sell your Two to Three=C2=A0Carat VV=
S1 Diamond Cluster Tranches to get a price for size and clarity, and then y=
ou get some correlation traders to bet on whether that premium will go up o=
r down. Financializing diamonds as a fungible standardized commodity is the=
 first step; financializing them back into individual diamonds is the next =
step.</p>
